AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; "Jerusalem will be in the hands of Muslims and the Muslim world will celebrate the liberation of Palestine." He wrote it on X the ayatollah Khamenei attaching to the post images of the Israeli contraerea that barks Iranian drones against the background of the Spianata delle Moschee.&nbsp; Iran and its allies left about 350 Iranian missiles and drones against Israel that contained a total of 60 tonnes of explosives. "We're still in the middle of a significant day of operation, after imagining Iran's attack," said IDF spokesman, Admiral Daniel Hagari, at a press conference "In the last few hours we have made evaluations and approved defense and attack plans." "The plan of Iran has failed," Hagari said, "on hundreds of launches, only a few missiles have entered the Israeli territory and have caused slight damage to the infrastructure of the base of the Nevatim Air Force." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
< blockquote
אל-קודס הקדושה תהיה בידי המוסלמים, והעולם המונהמוסמגייחגוגוני שחור פלסין. <a href="https://t.co/PB3wZk1jcN">pic.twitter.com/PB3wZk1jcN</a> — Khamenei.ir (@khamenei_ir)
<a href="https://twitter.com/khamenei_ir/status/1779576160088674681?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">April 14, 2024</a>
</blockquote
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Hezbollah congratulated Iran on the massive attack on Israel, stating that he "reached" his goals. In a statement, the Shiite group supported by Tehran expressed its "congratulations" to the ally for the "unprevious" attack against the common enemy Israel, ensuring that it has "reached" its military objectives "in spite of the response of the United States and its allies in the region". The Lebanese movement also welcomed Tehran's courageous and wise decision to respond firmly to the Zionist attack on the Iranian consulate in Damascus, Syria. The Saturday attack is the first ever made directly by Iran against the Israeli territory. According to the Israeli army, the attack was "invented" and "99% between missiles and drones" were intercepted. While the attack was underway, Hezbollah launched two Katyusha rockets against Israeli military positions on the Golan Heights.
&nbsp;
At the UN, Iran called on its right to self-defense, claiming that it had no choice. Iran "had no choice but to exercise its right to self-defense", said its ambassador to the UN, Amir Saeid Iravani, in front of the Security Council convened after the unprecedented Iranian attack against Israel. "The Security Council failed to fulfil its duty to maintain international peace and security" by not condemning the first April attack against the Iranian consulate in Damascus, and "in these conditions, the Islamic Republic of Iran has had no choice but to exercise its right to self-defense," he said, ensuring that Tehran does not want an escalation but will respond to "any threat or aggression". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
And by the way, Tehran threatened an even more violent reprisal if Israel decided to react to last night's attack and added that he was ready to hit the U.S. bases in the region. "Our response will be much wider than last night's military action if Israel reacts against Iran," said the state TV Chief of Staff of the Iranian Armed Forces, Major General Mohammad Bagheri, adding that Tehran warned Washington that any support for Israeli retaliation would result in that US bases would also be targeted. "If the Zionist regime or its supporters showed undesirable behavior, they would receive a decisive and much stronger response," said Iranian President Ebrahim Raisi, quoted by the Times of Israel. The commander of the Islamic revolutionary guards, Hossein Salami, also warned that Tehran will react against any Israeli attack on his interests, officials or citizens. He said that Tehran created a "new equation" in which any Israeli attack on his interests, assets, officials or citizens will be returned with attacks from his own territory. Salami also said that last night's operation was a success beyond expectations. Iranian Foreign Minister Hossein Amirabdollahian declared on Sunday in a meeting with foreign ambassadors in Tehran that his country informed the United States that his attacks against Israel will be "limited" and self-defense.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, the G7 leaders " stressed the need to avoid further escalation, inviting the parties to refrain from actions aimed at sharpening tension in the region. To this end, the G7 appealed to end the crisis in Gaza through the cessation of hostilities and the release of the hostages by Hamas. Finally, they ensured the continuation of humanitarian aid to the Palestinian population." The press release at the end of the summit of the 7 Great convened this morning by premier&nbsp;Meloni&nbsp;and held in the afternoon refers "to the joint declaration that firmly condemns the launch of drones and missiles from Iran, reaffirming full support to the security of Israel".
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
It goes in the direction of the strategy invoked by Italy with the President of the Council Giorgia&nbsp;Meloni&nbsp; that immediately after the attack of Tehran against Israel has activated on the diplomatic front to ensure that the conflict in the Middle East does not widen and that it works immediately to lower the tension. The G7 leaders' statement also contains a message to Iran that "has made further steps towards the destabilization of the region and is likely to cause uncontrollable regional escalation. This - the invitation - must be avoided. We will continue to work to stabilize the situation and avoid further escalation. In this spirit, we ask that Iran and its allies cease their attacks, and we are ready - the warning - to take further measures now and in response to further destabilizing initiatives". It is played on a double thread the management of the situation in the Middle East, after the move of Iran that is condemned "unnequivocally and in the strongest terms" for "direct and unprecedented attack against Israel". Western world leaders first express "solidarity and support for Israel and its people" and reaffirm "the commitment to its security". Italy, which has the G7 presidency, points out that the solution to the crisis must be diplomatic, the hope is that there are no further consequences after the rain of drones and missiles stopped from Tel Aviv thanks also to the support of the United States, Great Britain and France. And it's the American president Joe Biden who, in addition to announcing the G7 call, spent his time braking an immediate reaction from Israel.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
But the concern for what can happen in the next few days remains very strong. With the President of the Ue Ursula von der Leyen Commission expressing the possibility to put in place "more sanctions against Iran, in close collaboration with our partners, in particular on drone and missile programmes". But the goal, also pursued by the Italian government, is to point to caution. "This evening there are encouraging signals from both Tehran and Jerusalem, I think the invitation of the G7 to be prudent", the budget at the end of the day of the Foreign Minister and vicepremier&nbsp; Tajani. "Western diplomacy says Farnesina's manager is at work." The message sent to the parties involved in the conflict is to "do not start military operations", with Israel "who decided not to start attacks and suspended the attack on Rafah" Iran who concluded "the response operation to Israel's attack against the Iranian consulate in Syria". "It is not an easy situation", the secretary of Forza Italia admitted in the afternoon, also because the fear is linked also to what happens in the Red Sea ("I asked the Iranian Foreign Minister Amir-Abdollahian to become diligent part of the Houthi in order to make sure that they do not attack the Italian merchant ships", he underlined&nbsp;Tajani) and for the risk of actions of individual 'only objectives' In Italy the invitation to avoid further destabilization in the Middle East is 'bipartisan'. Among other things, the secretary dem Elly&nbsp;Schlein&nbsp; who called the President of the Council on the day to offer the "collaboration" of the Pd in the interest of Italy". The opposition request is that the executive report to Parliament as soon as possible. And already tomorrow, at 8 p.m., foreign and defence ministers,&nbsp;Tajani&nbsp;e&nbsp;Crosetto will be auditing the foreign and defence committees of Chamber and Senate to report on the Middle Eastern situation. &nbsp;
