&nbsp;
United States:> On 12 April the US Secretary of State Anthony Blinken had made a round of calls to ask China, Saudi Arabia and Turkey to mediate with Iran to avoid attacks that might have resulted in bad consequences. The White House has been working for months to prevent the conflict from spreading to the whole region. Blinken has made numerous tours in the area, passing also to Lebanon, where the Hezbollah, the allies of Tehran, which with Israel exchange blows directly from the border. The U.S., in the process of disengagement from Iraq and in the coming elections, do not want a burning Middle East, but continue to consider Tehran the number one enemy, more so after this attack. Europe Unnime condemns France, Germany and Italy and the EU countries. The European Union, through the president of the Ursula von der Leyen Commission, has called on Iran to "exist immediately attacks". In Brussels too, the elections are at the door and a large part of the public opinion in recent months has dissociated from the positions of the individual countries, considered too unbalanced in favour of Israel, in the light of the very serious humanitarian situation in Gaza. Europe behind the Iranian threat sees the spectrum of Islamic terrorism shakes and this is a factor that will help determine the outcome of the elections.
Canada and Great Britain support to Israel and condemn Iran, that British Prime Minister Rshi Sunak accuses of "voler sowing chaos". Apart from invitations to moderation from Ottawa, the two countries remained aligned with US foreign policy. However, in Britain, accusations have multiplied to the government and controversy over military supplies that continue to be guaranteed to Israel.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Ukraine and Russia two war countries, inevitably deployed on opposite sides; represent the emblem of the rift on the international geopolitical landscape. From October 7, Ukrainian President Volodimir Zelensky declared that "Hamas is like Russia, Israel as Ukraine." Words needed not to make the conflict pass in Ukraine and get the weapons to resist the attempts to break down the Moscow army. Iran's attack constituted Kiev the opportunity to stand against "two regimes that collaborate", two countries which are considered the most important members of the axis that threatens democracy. If to support groups like Hezbollah and Houthi, Tehran is thinking about it, to support Iran, Moscow is thinking about it. A thesis also based on the supplies of drones that Iran sends to Russia and with which the Russian army attacks Ukraine. The Kremlin kept the channels open with Hamas, with which it dialogues. Russian diplomacy has heard more about "new axis of power" with Tehran.
&nbsp;
Turkey>: Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan absolutely does not want the conflict to expand in the region and for months he has been working mainly to appease Hezbollah in Lebanon. At the same time Ankara and Tehran have been approached in recent months and the Turkish leader seems one of the few who has the possibility and intention to intervene on ayatollahs, as well as to dialogue with Moscow. Erdogan, however, pushes for a political solution, keeps the channels open with Hamas and has not spared accusations of genocide (as well as economic sanctions) against Israel. Waiting for a visit to the White House next May 9, the Turkish leader remains central counterpart in the area throughout the West. >
